'''Baichō''' (陪塚・ばいちょう・ばいづか, also '''Baichū''' 陪冢) refers to a style of [[kofun]] (ancient Kofuns) from Japan's [[Kofun period]].
== Overview ==
Baichō are smaller kofun constructed alongside large kofun, forming part of a [[kofun cluster]]. These smaller kofun were built contemporaneously with the central large kofun and are believed to have been intentionally planned as accompanying structures. They are thought to serve as burial sites for the relatives or retainers of the chieftains interred in the main kofun. Additionally, some baichō are believed to have been constructed to house {{ill|Grave goods|en|Grave goods|qid=Q1399692|lt=Grave goods|1=Grave goods}} associated with the burial rites of the main kofun's occupant.
